1
00:00:00,568 --> 00:00:02,103
[Music playing]

2
00:00:10,311 --> 00:00:11,645
[Shovel digs]

3
00:00:11,845 --> 00:00:13,647
[Girl panting]

4
00:00:32,266 --> 00:00:33,667
MAN: What the hell
was that?

5
00:00:33,867 --> 00:00:34,535
[Dogs barking]

6
00:00:34,735 --> 00:00:36,170
What the...
What was that?

7
00:00:38,506 --> 00:00:41,041
Molly?
What did you do?

8
00:00:41,242 --> 00:00:43,177
Relax. It was just
half an M-80 this time.

9
00:00:44,278 --> 00:00:45,546
Look, I made a crater.

10
00:00:45,746 --> 00:00:47,081
You have to come
to see this.

11
00:00:47,281 --> 00:00:48,116
I layered the sediment,

12
00:00:49,016 --> 00:00:49,083
And the ejecta
looks exactly...

13
00:00:49,917 --> 00:00:49,983
It's 4:30
in the morning.

14
00:00:50,818 --> 00:00:50,884
I swear,
I have neighbors.

15
00:00:51,752 --> 00:00:53,053
Why are you
doing this now?

16
00:00:53,954 --> 00:00:54,655
For Geology.
It's due tomorrow.

17
00:00:55,823 --> 00:00:58,126
Or today in, like,
3 1/2 hours actually, and...

18
00:00:58,326 --> 00:01:00,194
I have to get up
in the morning.
Remember that?

19
00:01:00,394 --> 00:01:03,597
I swear, at least
just one time,
I'm begging you,

20
00:01:03,797 --> 00:01:05,065
Just let me sleep
through the night.

21
00:01:05,266 --> 00:01:07,368
[Chuckles]

22
00:01:07,568 --> 00:01:09,403
There's gas lines
and water lines
down there.

23
00:01:09,603 --> 00:01:10,738
I checked.

24
00:01:11,872 --> 00:01:13,107
You can't just randomly
do stuff like this.

25
00:01:13,307 --> 00:01:14,442
I checked.
What?

26
00:01:15,643 --> 00:01:16,844
I had the utilities
come out yesterday and mark,

27
00:01:17,811 --> 00:01:19,147
And he did a survey,
and he marked.

28
00:01:19,347 --> 00:01:20,214
Look, I'm not stupid.

29
00:01:21,048 --> 00:01:22,183
And how much
did that cost?

30
00:01:23,217 --> 00:01:24,385
I... They spread it out
over the bills.

31
00:01:25,819 --> 00:01:28,088
Look, I just... It just
took me a lot longer
than I planned.

32
00:01:28,289 --> 00:01:29,757
A lot longer, and...

33
00:01:33,327 --> 00:01:36,230
All right, I'm up now.

34
00:01:36,430 --> 00:01:37,631
Show me what you're doing,
Professor.

35
00:01:37,831 --> 00:01:41,669
I wanted
to recreate craters
from volcanic eruptions,

36
00:01:41,869 --> 00:01:43,271
And I had
to do it here,

37
00:01:44,438 --> 00:01:44,872
Because the sedimentary
deposits are exactly...

38
00:01:46,106 --> 00:01:47,308
You couldn't have just made
a baking soda volcano?

39
00:01:48,376 --> 00:01:49,377
Well, as sad as I know
it makes you, Dad,

40
00:01:50,278 --> 00:01:51,779
I'm not in third grade
anymore.

41
00:01:51,979 --> 00:01:54,315
[Rumbling]

42
00:01:54,515 --> 00:01:56,384
Get out of there,
Molly!

43
00:01:57,918 --> 00:01:59,820
[Grunting]

44
00:02:00,020 --> 00:02:02,690
Molly, get out of there!

45
00:02:02,890 --> 00:02:04,358
Ow! Ow!
No, no, no, no!

46
00:02:04,558 --> 00:02:06,894
I'm really stuck!
It's stuck! It's stuck.

47
00:02:07,094 --> 00:02:08,296
Pull!
I'm trying!

48
00:02:08,496 --> 00:02:09,497
I can't!

49
00:02:09,697 --> 00:02:11,199
Pull harder!
I'm trying!

50
00:02:11,399 --> 00:02:12,433
I'm trying!
Oh, God!

51
00:02:14,535 --> 00:02:16,837
[Gasping]

52
00:02:17,037 --> 00:02:18,339
The whole house
is coming down!

53
00:02:18,539 --> 00:02:20,208
Come on, baby! Pull!

54
00:02:20,408 --> 00:02:21,542
Pull!

55
00:02:24,612 --> 00:02:26,280
Dad, you gotta
get out of here.

56
00:02:26,480 --> 00:02:27,415
No! No!

57
00:02:27,615 --> 00:02:29,350
Get out of here!

58
00:02:29,550 --> 00:02:30,718
Come here.
Come here.

59
00:02:36,390 --> 00:02:37,325
Daddy!

60
00:02:37,525 --> 00:02:38,892
Daddy!

61
00:02:45,533 --> 00:02:47,468
[Dogs barking]

62
00:02:49,770 --> 00:02:51,739
[Music playing]

63
00:03:53,033 --> 00:03:54,402
WOMAN: Hey, guys!

64
00:03:54,602 --> 00:03:55,936
Uh, okay, it looks like

65
00:03:56,136 --> 00:03:58,906
We'll be out of cell range
till Monday at least.

66
00:03:59,106 --> 00:04:00,674
Uh, most
of the San Andreas Fault

67
00:04:00,874 --> 00:04:02,009
Is pretty much
in the boonies.

68
00:04:02,209 --> 00:04:03,611
We're up near Paso Robles

69
00:04:03,811 --> 00:04:05,779
Putting in the next set
of sensors,

70
00:04:05,979 --> 00:04:07,515
And if all goes well,

71
00:04:07,715 --> 00:04:10,318
We'll have them all in
by tomorrow evening.

72
00:04:10,518 --> 00:04:13,321
And I cannot wait
to come home.

73
00:04:13,521 --> 00:04:14,688
I've missed you both.

74
00:04:14,888 --> 00:04:16,790
So good night.

75
00:04:16,990 --> 00:04:18,626
Bye.

76
00:04:28,135 --> 00:04:31,972
MAN: Molly? Molly,
where are you?

77
00:04:32,172 --> 00:04:33,441
Oh, another
all-nighter, huh?

78
00:04:33,641 --> 00:04:34,475
Science doesn't sleep.

79
00:04:35,309 --> 00:04:35,909
Heh.
But normal people do.

80
00:04:36,744 --> 00:04:38,278
I did.
I just got up early.

81
00:04:39,146 --> 00:04:40,280
Done.

82
00:04:41,549 --> 00:04:43,951
Yes!

83
00:04:44,151 --> 00:04:46,019
Ah, it was just
a bad power supply.

84
00:04:46,219 --> 00:04:49,790
All 19 sensors are
up and running perfectly.

85
00:04:49,990 --> 00:04:51,058
Make you some eggs?

86
00:04:51,258 --> 00:04:52,726
Oh, no, no, no.
I made breakfast.

87
00:04:52,926 --> 00:04:55,295
Wait. What? Heh.
Since when?

88
00:04:55,496 --> 00:04:57,765
Since I thought it
would melt the ice storm
with Miss you-know-who.

89
00:04:57,965 --> 00:04:59,066
I thought we could
all eat together.

90
00:04:59,266 --> 00:05:00,067
Oh, that's sweet,

91
00:05:00,934 --> 00:05:01,935
But I told you
I'm taking up

92
00:05:03,070 --> 00:05:03,637
A couple of lovebirds
at 8:00 this morning.

93
00:05:04,538 --> 00:05:04,972
I only got
a couple of minutes.

94
00:05:05,506 --> 00:05:06,674
What? When?

95
00:05:07,975 --> 00:05:09,710
Last night,
when you were futzing
with your iPad.

96
00:05:10,944 --> 00:05:12,413
Shoot!

97
00:05:12,613 --> 00:05:14,548
Maybe I should have
sent you a text message.

98
00:05:14,748 --> 00:05:15,749
No, it's okay.
I'm sorry.

99
00:05:15,949 --> 00:05:17,585
I've been distracted.

100
00:05:17,785 --> 00:05:19,453
And working
a little too hard?

101
00:05:19,653 --> 00:05:20,788
No, look, I'm sorry.

102
00:05:21,922 --> 00:05:22,723
I'm just getting
really close. These swarms.

103
00:05:24,191 --> 00:05:26,627
You know, we've had
12 minor M1 quakes
in the last 72 hours.

104
00:05:26,827 --> 00:05:28,362
Something's up,
something big.

105
00:05:28,562 --> 00:05:30,831
I don't feel like I have
any time to waste.

106
00:05:31,031 --> 00:05:33,867
Well, I'm sure
you'll figure it out.
I know you will.

107
00:05:34,067 --> 00:05:36,537
At least let me
get you some toast.

108
00:05:37,638 --> 00:05:39,440
Oh.

109
00:05:39,640 --> 00:05:40,841
You like yours
well done, right?

110
00:05:41,041 --> 00:05:42,776
[Chuckles]
Perfect.

111
00:05:44,778 --> 00:05:46,380
Is Ali awake?

112
00:05:46,580 --> 00:05:47,848
I made
her favorites,

113
00:05:49,116 --> 00:05:50,751
French toast
with mascarpone
and turkey sausage.

114
00:05:50,951 --> 00:05:52,953
You know
how to make all that?

115
00:05:53,153 --> 00:05:56,089
No, but there's these
wonderful little books
that I found

116
00:05:56,289 --> 00:05:57,791
With step-by-step
instructions.

117
00:05:59,059 --> 00:06:00,528
Cooking books,
I think that's
what you call them.

118
00:06:00,728 --> 00:06:01,695
She'll come around.

119
00:06:01,895 --> 00:06:03,363
I hope so.
Eventually.

120
00:06:03,564 --> 00:06:05,098
Stepmoms are
no competition

121
00:06:05,298 --> 00:06:07,568
For the influence
of a new boyfriend.

122
00:06:07,768 --> 00:06:08,769
Mm.

123
00:06:09,803 --> 00:06:10,938
I figure when
that relationship ends,

124
00:06:12,205 --> 00:06:14,542
And I hope soon,
that she'll turn
to me again

125
00:06:14,742 --> 00:06:17,478
And I could convince her
to go back to school.

126
00:06:17,678 --> 00:06:18,479
Mm-hmm.

127
00:06:18,679 --> 00:06:20,548
[Beeping]
Oh.

128
00:06:20,748 --> 00:06:21,815
[Sighs]
Just a minute.

129
00:06:22,015 --> 00:06:23,150
Right.
Hold on.

130
00:06:23,350 --> 00:06:25,152
Morning, Ali.
I made you
breakfast.

131
00:06:25,352 --> 00:06:27,755
Dad. Molly.

132
00:06:27,955 --> 00:06:29,122
Really?
Hank.

133
00:06:29,322 --> 00:06:31,559
Thanks,
but I gotta run.

134
00:06:31,759 --> 00:06:34,595
But it's French toast
with mascarpone.

135
00:06:34,795 --> 00:06:36,063
Trying to watch
what I eat,

136
00:06:36,263 --> 00:06:37,798
All that sugar and carbs.

137
00:06:37,998 --> 00:06:39,933
Oh, please.
You're a rail.

138
00:06:40,133 --> 00:06:41,502
I gotta jet anyway.

139
00:06:41,702 --> 00:06:42,736
You know
how long it takes

140
00:06:42,936 --> 00:06:44,004
To get from Rosemead
to downtown?

141
00:06:44,204 --> 00:06:45,606
Why do we even live here?

142
00:06:46,874 --> 00:06:47,675
Because Rosemead
sits on a giant slab
of granite,

143
00:06:48,542 --> 00:06:48,876
And that's
exactly where you

144
00:06:49,943 --> 00:06:50,611
Want to be
when an earthquake
strikes.

145
00:06:51,845 --> 00:06:52,913
Well, it's not where you
want to be when you're 18.

146
00:06:54,214 --> 00:06:55,182
Well, why don't you
have your boyfriend
over here?

147
00:06:55,949 --> 00:06:56,584
We can
all have dinner.

148
00:06:57,585 --> 00:06:57,918
There's no boy.
See you later, Dad.

149
00:06:59,853 --> 00:07:01,655
You think
your passengers
want breakfast?

150
00:07:01,855 --> 00:07:03,957
[Chuckles]
I have plenty.

151
00:07:04,157 --> 00:07:07,427
Put it in the fridge.
I'll have it for dinner.

152
00:07:07,628 --> 00:07:10,598
And for one day, try to
not think of earthquakes.

153
00:07:12,633 --> 00:07:14,568
ANCHOR:
A series of minor temblors

154
00:07:14,768 --> 00:07:16,770
Causes jitters
throughout the Southland.

155
00:07:16,970 --> 00:07:18,506
Two dozen tiny earthquakes

156
00:07:18,706 --> 00:07:21,208
Registering 1.0
on the Richter Scale or lower

157
00:07:21,408 --> 00:07:24,478
Has seismotologists scratching
their heads this morning,

158
00:07:24,678 --> 00:07:26,814
While the string
of temblors seems to have gone

159
00:07:27,014 --> 00:07:29,016
Largely unnoticed
for most Los Angelenos.

160
00:07:29,216 --> 00:07:31,619
We'll check in with Tippi Santos
at Venice Beach,

161
00:07:31,819 --> 00:07:34,488
And your weather report
from Kaz.

162
00:07:35,956 --> 00:07:38,158
MOLLY: Okay, now with
this final piece in place,

163
00:07:38,358 --> 00:07:40,594
All 19 sensors
along the entire fault line

164
00:07:40,794 --> 00:07:41,795
Are gonna start
pinging each other,

165
00:07:42,863 --> 00:07:43,997
And the system
is gonna crunch that data

166
00:07:45,098 --> 00:07:46,500
And send me back reports.
And when we take

167
00:07:48,001 --> 00:07:49,970
All the data streams
from all the sensors,
we get this. Danny?

168
00:07:50,170 --> 00:07:52,039
Hold on
to your butts.

169
00:07:52,239 --> 00:07:56,009
Each sensor monitors
microseismic activity,

170
00:07:56,209 --> 00:07:58,612
And that's the changing
ratio between sheer waves

171
00:07:58,812 --> 00:08:01,481
And pressure waves
within a 50-mile radius.

172
00:08:01,682 --> 00:08:04,518
Real-time monitoring?
That's nothing new.

173
00:08:04,718 --> 00:08:06,019
No, not just
real-time monitoring.

174
00:08:06,219 --> 00:08:08,055
Predictive extrapolations

175
00:08:08,255 --> 00:08:09,857
For all
microquake activities

176
00:08:10,057 --> 00:08:11,992
Along the entire
San Andreas Fault.

177
00:08:12,192 --> 00:08:15,663
See these white circles?
They're microquakes.

178
00:08:15,863 --> 00:08:18,666
Can anyone tell me
the importance
of the microquake?

179
00:08:20,033 --> 00:08:21,702
Well, they're important,
because...

180
00:08:21,902 --> 00:08:23,103
Because some
theorize they could be

181
00:08:23,303 --> 00:08:24,104
Good predictors
for foreshocks

182
00:08:24,938 --> 00:08:26,139
Or even quakes
themselves.

183
00:08:26,339 --> 00:08:28,075
And if we were
in the business

184
00:08:28,275 --> 00:08:29,643
Of predicting earthquakes,
the microquake

185
00:08:29,843 --> 00:08:31,679
Would be
our best source of data.

186
00:08:31,879 --> 00:08:34,548
But it can't be done,
'cause it's
not possible.

187
00:08:34,748 --> 00:08:36,516
What can't?
Predicting quakes.

188
00:08:38,085 --> 00:08:38,952
Well, that might be true,
but I happen to believe
that it can be.

189
00:08:40,187 --> 00:08:41,221
Yeah, and how'd
that work out
for you in 2008?

190
00:08:42,355 --> 00:08:43,824
[Giggles]

191
00:08:44,024 --> 00:08:45,025
[Sighs]

192
00:08:45,225 --> 00:08:48,228
Well, someone's done
their homework for once.

193
00:08:48,428 --> 00:08:50,130
Yes, I was wrong.
I guess you could say

194
00:08:50,330 --> 00:08:52,633
I acted before I had
all the data. I was hasty.

195
00:08:52,833 --> 00:08:54,134
But this is different.

196
00:08:54,334 --> 00:08:54,935
Here's the catch.

197
00:08:55,135 --> 00:08:57,304
See these white circles?

198
00:08:57,504 --> 00:08:58,639
They're microquakes,

199
00:08:59,539 --> 00:08:59,907
And they haven't
happened yet.

200
00:09:00,540 --> 00:09:01,108
But I will bet you

201
00:09:02,042 --> 00:09:02,676
Dollars to doughnuts,
they will,

202
00:09:03,711 --> 00:09:04,845
And in an hour's time,
to be specific.

203
00:09:05,813 --> 00:09:06,880
And in predicting
the microquake,

204
00:09:07,881 --> 00:09:08,816
We can further
extrapolate that data

205
00:09:10,050 --> 00:09:11,885
Into exponentially bigger,
more timely predictions.

206
00:09:12,085 --> 00:09:13,887
[Scoffs]
I don't buy it.

207
00:09:14,087 --> 00:09:16,890
And that's all the time
we have for today.

208
00:09:17,090 --> 00:09:18,926
Come get
your graded field reports.

209
00:09:19,126 --> 00:09:20,027
Really good job, everybody.

210
00:09:20,928 --> 00:09:21,294
And if you have
any questions,

211
00:09:22,262 --> 00:09:22,963
I'll be in the campus café,
okay?

212
00:09:39,780 --> 00:09:41,949
All right.

213
00:09:42,149 --> 00:09:43,216
Come on.

214
00:09:43,416 --> 00:09:44,685
[Sighs]

215
00:09:44,885 --> 00:09:45,953
Show me
something good.

216
00:09:48,488 --> 00:09:50,758
I deserve an "A."
What?

217
00:09:50,958 --> 00:09:52,860
I need it.
I could lose
my scholarship.

218
00:09:53,060 --> 00:09:54,127
You should have
studied more.

219
00:09:54,327 --> 00:09:55,328
I'm trying, okay,

220
00:09:56,396 --> 00:09:57,665
But do you know
how many classes I have,

221
00:09:57,865 --> 00:09:58,999
How much I have to read?

222
00:09:59,199 --> 00:10:00,668
I'm working
all the time.

223
00:10:00,868 --> 00:10:01,969
"A" students
make the time.

224
00:10:04,204 --> 00:10:07,307
I have a problem with
know-it-all students who
show a lot of promise

225
00:10:07,507 --> 00:10:10,377
And squander it all away
on girls and drinking.
I know your type.

226
00:10:10,577 --> 00:10:11,745
You read
"On the Road" once,

227
00:10:12,780 --> 00:10:13,380
And suddenly you have
all the answers.

228
00:10:14,281 --> 00:10:15,348
I'm not seeing
a lot of girls.

229
00:10:16,717 --> 00:10:17,317
I might just be
a teacher, but I hear
all the gossip.

230
00:10:18,518 --> 00:10:20,120
And that's great.
You should be
having fun.

231
00:10:20,320 --> 00:10:21,388
But just because
you're smart, Nick...

232
00:10:22,489 --> 00:10:23,190
[Cellphone ringing]
And you really are.

233
00:10:24,557 --> 00:10:25,993
I can see
what you're capable of
when you actually try.

234
00:10:27,294 --> 00:10:28,261
But it doesn't mean
you don't have
to do the work.

235
00:10:28,461 --> 00:10:29,629
[Ring]

236
00:10:29,830 --> 00:10:31,832
Now excuse me.

237
00:10:32,032 --> 00:10:32,833
Hey.

238
00:10:33,033 --> 00:10:34,134
Hey. You okay?

239
00:10:34,334 --> 00:10:35,302
Yeah, I'm fine.
Just a student.

240
00:10:36,336 --> 00:10:37,037
Same old, same old.
Any word from Ali

241
00:10:38,005 --> 00:10:38,806
On her first day
at the front desk?

242
00:10:40,107 --> 00:10:41,341
You know Ali. She's probably
running that hotel by now.

243
00:10:41,541 --> 00:10:43,243
She can fend
for herself.

244
00:10:43,443 --> 00:10:44,978
Too true.
You taking off yet?

245
00:10:45,178 --> 00:10:46,246
I'm gassing up right now.

246
00:10:46,446 --> 00:10:47,748
Hey, how was
the field trip?

247
00:10:47,948 --> 00:10:49,983
It was fine, except for

248
00:10:50,183 --> 00:10:51,852
The aforementioned student
brought up 2008.

249
00:10:52,052 --> 00:10:54,121
Ah, forget 2008.

250
00:10:54,321 --> 00:10:56,389
Remember that Edison
failed, like, 10,000 times

251
00:10:56,589 --> 00:10:58,025
Before he invented
the lightbulb, right?

252
00:10:59,326 --> 00:11:00,761
You mean,
before he stole it
and patented the idea?

253
00:11:00,961 --> 00:11:02,095
[Chuckles]
I'm just nervous.

254
